<TITLE> 1 in 5 New Year UK babies may become obese </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 LONDON, Jan 1(bdnews24.com/Reuters) - One in five babies born in Britain today could be obese by the time they start school unless action is taken to tackle overeating and overfeeding, health authorities said on Friday. Public health minister Gillian Merron said more than 300 of the 1,500 babies likely to be born on New Year's day could be overweight or obese by around the age of five and urged new mothers to focus on developing a good diet. "What happens in the first years of a baby's life has a big effect on how healthy they are in the future," she said in a statement. "Obesity levels are still too high." Obesity levels are rising across the world and threatening to overwhelm health care systems and government health budgets with the costs of handling the high number of cases of diabetes, heart disease and cancer that being overweight can cause. A report last month found one in 10 children in England will be obese by 2015, with the poorest at far greater risk than the rich. Merron outlined a campaign with tips aimed at getting new mothers to develop healthy eating habits in their children. It included encouraging breastfeeding, not starting solid foods too early, offering a variety of foods, discouraging sweet foods and keeping babies and young children act
